   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1812_08_03_image01.jpg"/>
            <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
            <opener>
               <dateline><!--If there's no date line, remove this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworthtown</placeName>
                  <date when="1812-08-03">August 03, 1812</date></dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>
               I will not heap coals of fire upon your<lb/>
               head by telling you how much we are<lb/>
               not only disappointed but mortified by<lb/>
               your letter - <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Bowood-House_ENK">Bowood!</placeName> <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Bowood-House_ENK">Bowood!</placeName> -<lb/>
               Why you can be at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Bowood-House_ENK">Bowood</placeName> any <choice><orig>sum-<lb/>-mer</orig><reg>summer</reg></choice>
               of your life - but at my advanced<lb/>
               age it should have been <hi rend="underline">this</hi> summer<lb/>
               for <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworthtown</placeName> - for the coming<lb/>
               of another summer for me is not<lb/>
               what I depend upon -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               Your habits of a <hi rend="underline">French man of Letters</hi><lb/>
               have taken strange hold of you -<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2"> M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> E.</persName> laughed, <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName> scolded, &amp; I<lb/>
               pitied you -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               Your original mistake in the whole<lb/>
               business was laying in <unclear>silence</unclear> so come<lb/>
               here for a few days - what we wished<lb/>
               I dare not say expected, was that you<lb/>
               would come &amp; stay some time with<lb/>
               us - that we might really enjoy your<lb/>
               conversation, not be, merely <hi rend="underline">flattered</hi><lb/>
               by your visit - I had stored up<lb/>
               for myself the pleasure of telling you<lb/>
               that your second volume is delightfully<lb/>
               
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1812_08_03_image02.jpg"/>
               written, <del><unclear>of silly</unclear></del> as lively as we could <unclear>wish</unclear><lb/>
               it to be, and to convince you that we<lb/>
               thought so you would have seen your<lb/>
               book full of <hi rend="underline">marks</hi> and our minds<lb/>
               full of all your useful lessons.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               We had put off all engagements<lb/>
               &amp; would permit nobody to come to<lb/>
               see us, till we had seen you -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               Travelling by night in a mail coach<lb/>
               is fit only for a postman - but by a<lb/>
               little contrivance a man may travel<lb/>
               by day in different coaches &amp; may<lb/>
               stop in different towns on his journey<lb/>
               &amp; may see &amp; hear a great deal of what<lb/>
               is useful &amp; entertaining - your<lb/>
               journey <del><unclear>here wa</unclear></del> in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName> would<lb/>
               have been quite easy - you would<lb/>
               have reached this place in one day<lb/>
               from <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dublin_IE">Dublin</placeName> with great ease-<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               You say that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LansH1">Lord Lansdowne</persName><lb/>
               had thoughts of visiting <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName>.<lb/>
               - How can statesmen talk so much<lb/>
               about <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName> and take so little trouble<lb/>
               to see it ? His <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LansH1">Lordship</persName> gave it under<lb/>
               the hand of a Peer that he would come<lb/>
               to see us if he should ever come to<lb/>
               
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1812_08_03_image03.jpg"/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName> - and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LansL1">Lady L.</persName> told my son <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeC1">Sneyd</persName><lb/>
               that she had no objection to be of the<lb/>
               party -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I am determined to cultivate <hi rend="underline">Egoism</hi><lb/>
               for the rest of my life!<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#Volta1">Voltaire</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SwifJ1">Swift</persName> cried vive la bagatelle<lb/>
               I exclaim Vive le' Egoisme.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               You speak of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StaeA1">Madame de Stael</persName><lb/>
               but not of her admirable book <del><unclear>Som</unclear></del><lb/>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Litte1">Influence de la Literature'</title> &amp;c.<lb/>
               You talk <add>of sending</add> to us <del><unclear>of extracts of</unclear></del> morsels<lb/>
               of literature &amp; morality - We will have<lb/>
               none of them but from your lips!!<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               What you say of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Marias</persName> tales<lb/>
               is just - But they are not given<lb/>
               as Epics but simply as <hi rend="underline">tales</hi>. -<lb/>
               and to make them better for the<lb/>
               best tastes would be to make<lb/>
               them worse for general <hi rend="underline">consumption</hi><lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               She has another tale to finish - in<lb/>
               three volumes - this will be of a higher<lb/>
               flight - but it will perhaps be not so<lb/>
               popular - adieu -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I would not, at near seventy years of<lb/>
               age, be encumbered with so much<lb/>
               
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1812_08_03_image03.jpg"/>
               vis inertia as you are loaded with,<lb/>
               for a Dukedom!<lb/>
               
               
            </p>
            
            <closer>
               Yours truly - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">Rich <hi rend="superscript">d</hi> Lovell Edgeworth</persName>
            </closer>
            
